node.text: We still have time, but not a lot of it. So let’s not lose hope, but let’s use this as fuel and energy to keep going, to keep fighting, to keep caring ✊

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Chicks For Climate on July 29, 2021. May be an image of sky and text that says 'IS CLIMATE CHANGE STILL REVERSIBLE? There's been a lot in the news about climate-related climate- disasters recently. Can we still take action to save the planet and its inhabitants? CHICKS CLIMATE FOR'.

Photo by Chicks For Climate on July 29, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'GOVERNMENTS ARE STILL STALLING Extreme flooding in Europe, record- breaking heatwaves in the Pacific Northwest, and torrential rain in China. Understandably, these headlines are exacerbating fears and eco-anxiety. The Paris Climate Agreement vows to keep global warming to below 1.5 degrees c to avoid the very worst of the effects of climate change. Almost no country, is on track to meet their proposed emission cuts, which on their own still wouldn't keep warming to below 1.5 CHICKS FOR CLIMATE'.

Photo by Chicks For Climate on July 29, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'sO IS ALL HOPEL LOST? No. According to WeForum, we will cross the 1.5 Cthreshold between 2027 and 2042. However, this means it's not enough anymore to make individual changes. There isn't enough time. The system needs to change immediately. CHICKS CLIMATE FOR'.

Photo by Chicks For Climate on July 29, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'COP26 MAY BE OUR LAST CHANCE COP26 the UN Climate Change Conference- is less than 100 days away. Countries will need to be convinced to: Phase out coal Stop deforestation Speed up the switch to electric vehicles Encourage investment in renewables CHICKS CLIMATE FOR'.

Photo by Chicks For Climate on July 29, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'WHAT CAN I DO? As citizens of our respective countries, we have the power of our voice to convince and pressure politicians to take action. Tweet your leaders, email them, call them, talk to family and friends about the urgency of the climate crisis, take action in your local community. Our politicians are elected by us- they (theoretically) represent our needs and concerns. Making those concerns known is the most important step you can take as a citizen of your country. CHICKS CLRATE'.
Photo by Chicks For Climate on July 27, 2021. May be an image of book and text that says 'Let's talk about food apartheid. CHICKS c00 CLIMATE'.

node.text:
There are 20 Central Parks worth of empty lots in Los Angeles. Imagine what we could do with that space if we planted fresh fruits and vegetables. Imagine how many people would be well fed. And now extrapolate that to the whole world. 

This is an important one - swipe through and learn what food apartheid is and the people doing the important grassroots work. 🌾

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Chicks For Climate on July 27, 2021. May be an image of book and text that says 'Let's talk about food apartheid. CHICKS c00 CLIMATE'.

Photo by Chicks For Climate on July 27, 2021. May be an image of text that says '54.5 million people in the US live in low-income areas with poor access to healthy food. More than ạ million people in the UK live in neighbourhoods with severely limited access to fresh fruit and vegetables. This is called food apartheid. And it didn't happen by accident. For years, urban planning and redlining has favoured predominantly white, high-income communities, which have an average of four times as many_ supermarkets as predominantly Black communities. CHICKS CLIMATE'.

Photo by Chicks For Climate on July 27, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'The food system needs to change. The majority of farmers around the world are women and people of colour. Non profit food 'banks are mostly white-led and operate in communities of colour. Food banks have been operating in low income communities for decades, but food insecurity has only_gotten worse. As a response to the lack of accountability from government to address these problems, food activists have created grassroots movements to feed and nourish these communities until government and policy can step iท. Swipe to meet two of them! CHICKS CLIMATE'.

Photo shared by Chicks For Climate on July 27, 2021 tagging @karwasher. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Meet the activists. Food justice activist Karen Washington coined the term "food apartheid" She says that the food system is not broken, but working exactly as was designed. She cofounded "Black Urban Growers' an organisation supporting farmers working in urban and rural settings. p 201 cuer llas arss Tars CHICKS CLIMATE'.

Photo shared by Chicks For Climate on July 27, 2021 tagging @ronfinleyhq. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Meet the activists. Ron Fịnley is a fashion designer turned grower and food activist living in LA, and plants as a form of protest against the "food prison" he described his neighborhood turning into. "People looked at my garden like your little hobby' or something, now people realise this is no damn hobby, this is life and death. This IS our revolution." CHICKS CLIMATE'.

node.text:
In a world that requires us to constantly be consuming and being exploited to make a handful of people really rich, taking the time to pause and care for yourself non monetarily is radical. 

This weekend, if you can, take time to:
🍃 be in nature 
💨 breathe 
✍️ pause to write 
🫂 hug a loved one 

Graphic by @rinnyriot ✨✨✨

node.text:
It shouldn’t have to happen to you for it to matter to you. The poorest and most oppressed in wealthy societies will suffer the most, but let’s not forget that poorer countries have already been experiencing massive effects of climate change, without the luxury of big budgets to clean up the mess. Sadly all the power to fix this is in the hands of the govts of the Global North. 

Slides via our friends at @earthrise.studio ⭐️

node.text:
The fragility of white masculinity is on full display in the wake of England’s loss. Just look at the horrific racial abuse aimed at players like Rashford and Saka. No one should have to fear for their lives or safety as a result of a football game. Disappointed, but not surprised.

Source: The Economist, “Domestic violence surges after a football match ends”
